    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.25.15-16_0001"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>August 17, '57</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>My apologies for the long silence, but things have twisted <del>in</del><add>out of</add> my hands. I finished the rough draft near the end of July and my adviser returned it promptly, but with instructions to cut. The department prefers brief dissertations. Mine runs about 275 pages. I <unclear/> the detail in agony, trying to include in one area what was bypassed in another &#8212; so that as record at any rate it would include the gist of critical biography. But to get it down to the absolute maximum of 240 pages, I have had to rip out much of the biographical detail including some favorite scraps from your letters to Mona, most of the comment in contemporary reviews. Now I cannot <hi rend="underline">feel</hi> or see what is that the thing as a whole now says.</p>
                
                <p>As you know I would, I tried hard for a clear and true statement so far as my limited vision extends. While my aim is primarily descriptive, statements or implications of judgment inevitably occur. But I was not fearful of adverse judgments &#8212; you
                
                    <fw type="curatorial">15</fw>
               
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.25.15-16_0002a"/>
                
                    are immune to praise or blame, certainly from a nobody. What really disturbs me is that what I have come to admire most in John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt is the <hi rend="underline">man</hi> &#8212; and the <hi rend="underline">man</hi> is being sacrificed to my degree. Yet the fault finally is my own &#8212; I <unclear>agreed</unclear> against straight critical biography on the grounds that it would necessarily violate the privacy of your life &#8212; and that inevitably it would not present you as you know yourself (has Johnson clubbed Boswell across the Styx?), would therefore give you pain and made me a most ungrateful dog.</p>
                
                <p>So here I am with something whittled down to a about 235 pages &#8212; something that now seems a puzzle. I have omitted much more than I have included. It may be that just for psychic relief I may be compelled, once this hurdle is behind, to rewrite the whole thing and see if I can <del>portray</del> draw you in my own fashion.</p>
                
                <p>But for the moment &#8212; I do not know whether I will get down to see you this summer. The reductions of biography
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.25.15-16_0002b"/>
                
                    cancel<del>le</del> most of my questions, and this summer the dissertation <unclear>makes</unclear> all decisions. The few that still apply can probably be attended to by mail, unless you disown me.</p>
                
                <p>To be as little bother as possible, I'll wait until I can get them all together and then either send or bring them. What I really look forward to, however, is to see you all again, dissertation or not. And I am beginning to be eager, too, for you to tell me off on all the mistakes you find in that academic chore.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Love,</salute>
                    <signed>Paul</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <note type="curatorial"><hi rend="caps">JOHN G. NEIHARDT CENTER</hi></note>
                  
